SENATE BILL No. 279
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
business and other associations.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 23-21 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
2 A NEW ARTICLE TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1,
3 2026]:
4 ARTICLE 21. PRIVATE CREDIT FUNDS
5 Chapter 1. Applicability
6 Sec. 1. This article applies to investment information that is
7 delivered or communicated to an Indiana investor or the
8 commissioner after June 30, 2026.
9 Chapter 2. Definitions
10 Sec. 1. "Commissioner" means the securities commissioner
11 appointed under IC 23-19-6-1(a).
12 Sec. 2. "Deliver" or "delivery" means any method of delivery
13 used in conventional commercial practice, including delivery by
14 hand, mail, commercial delivery, and electronic transmission.
15 Sec. 3. "Disclosure", with respect to a private credit fund,
16 means information that:
17 (1) is included in investment information; and
2026 IN 279—LS 7102/DI 101

2
1 (2) sets forth information as to terms, objectives, risks,
2 performance, investment strategy, management, fees, and
3 other information:
4 (A) related to the private credit fund; and
5 (B) necessary for investors or potential investors to make
6 informed investment decisions.
7 Sec. 4. "Fund manager" means a firm or organization that
8 manages a private credit fund.
9 Sec. 5. "Indiana investor", with respect to a private credit fund,
10 means:
11 (1) an individual investor whose principal residence is in
12 Indiana; or
13 (2) an institutional investor that is domiciled in Indiana.
14 Sec. 6. "Investment information" means:
15 (1) an investor report;
16 (2) a circular;
17 (3) a prospectus;
18 (4) marketing material; or
19 (5) any similar investment information or promotional
20 material;
21 that concerns a private credit fund.
22 Sec. 7. "Private credit fund" means a fund that:
23 (1) pools capital from investors to make loans directly to
24 private businesses, bypassing traditional financial institutions;
25 (2) earns income from:
26 (A) base interest rates;
27 (B) spread; and
28 (C) deal fees;
29 associated with the loans made;
30 (3) may not be available to the general investing public;
31 (4) may require investors to:
32 (A) be accredited or meet specified asset, income, net
33 worth, or professional criteria;
34 (B) make substantial minimum investments; or
35 (C) commit their capital over substantial minimum time
36 frames; and
37 (5) may make loans to borrowers that:
38 (A) have credit ratings that are below investment grade; or
39 (B) do not qualify for loans offered by financial
40 institutions.
41 Chapter 3. Disclosure Requirements
42 Sec. 1. (a) After June 30, 2026, the responsible party or fund
2026 IN 279—LS 7102/DI 101

3
1 manager for a private credit fund shall deliver to:
2 (1) an Indiana investor that has invested capital in the private
3 credit fund; and
4 (2) the commissioner;
5 an investor report on at least a quarterly basis. The responsible
6 party or fund manager shall deliver an investor report to the
7 commissioner in the manner prescribed by the commissioner.
8 (b) An investor report required under this section must include,
9 at a minimum, the following disclosures, current as of the end of
10 the quarter to which the report pertains:
11 (1) The following investment returns for the private credit
12 fund, reported both inclusive and exclusive of fees:
13 (A) One (1) month return.
14 (B) Three (3) month return.
15 (C) Rolling twelve (12) month return.
16 (D) Return since inception.
17 (2) The number of loans in the fund's portfolio.
18 (3) The number of loans with outstanding balances that
19 represent more than five percent (5%) of the portfolio's value.
20 (4) A summary of the geographic spread of the portfolio's
21 loans.
22 (5) The number of loans in arrears, broken down by the
23 number of months in arrears.
24 (6) The number of loans with payment-in-kind interest
25 arrangements, including the percentage of the portfolio's
26 value those loans represent.
27 (7) The range of interest rates applicable to loans in the
28 portfolio, including a breakdown of loans with fixed rates and
29 floating interest rates.
30 (8) The types and amounts of fees paid by borrowers in the
31 fund's loan portfolio, including:
32 (A) the percentage of those fees retained by the fund or
33 fund manager; and
34 (B) the percentage of those fees distributed to investors.
35 (9) The proportion of investor distributions paid from:
36 (A) cash income from investments, including interest
37 payments and fees paid by borrowers in the fund's loan
38 portfolio; and
39 (B) other sources.
40 (10) The level of fund gearing, including both fund-level
41 leverage and portfolio-level leverage, expressed as a:
42 (A) debt to equity ratio; or
2026 IN 279—LS 7102/DI 101

4
1 (B) percentage.
2 (11) The proportion of loans in the portfolio that are
3 unsecured, including an assessment of the associated risks.
4 (12) For the secured portion of the portfolio:
5 (A) the nature of the security or collateral; and
6 (B) the percentage of the portfolio's value the secured
7 portion represents.
8 (13) Default and loss statistics for the portfolio's loans,
9 including a definition of what constitutes default under the
10 terms of the loans.
11 (14) An identification of, and contact information for, the
12 fund manager, including:
13 (A) legal name;
14 (B) any trade name under which the fund manager does
15 business;
16 (C) principal business address; and
17 (D) telephone number.
18 Sec. 2. (a) Any investment information that is delivered or
19 communicated to an Indiana investor after June 30, 2026, may not
20 include language or terms that positively describe the risk profile
21 of a private credit fund unless:
22 (1) a disclaimer is provided; or
23 (2) the fund's assets are rated by an outside credit rating
24 agency.
25 (b) Any information included on a publicly accessible web page
26 maintained by the fund manager is subject to the restrictions set
27 forth in subsection (a).
28 Sec. 3. The responsible party or fund manager for a private
29 credit fund shall, upon the written request of an Indiana investor
30 or the commissioner, make available in writing the fund manager's
31 policies on the following:
32 (1) Valuation practices with respect to the fund's loans,
33 including the frequency of valuations.
34 (2) Liquidity management.
35 (3) Credit risk assessment, including the frequency of
36 assessments.
37 (4) Borrower default management.
38 (5) Conflicts of interest.
39 Chapter 4. Administration and Enforcement
40 Sec. 1. The commissioner shall adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to
41 implement and administer this article.
42 Sec. 2. The commissioner may use any lawful means within the
2026 IN 279—LS 7102/DI 101

5
1 commissioner's authority to enforce this article.
2 Sec. 3. In connection with the administration and enforcement
3 of this article, the attorney general shall provide all necessary
4 assistance to the commissioner upon the commissioner's request.
5 Sec. 4. IC 4-21.5 and any rules of practice adopted by the
6 securities division are applicable to any administrative proceeding
7 arising out of the administration or enforcement of this article.
